<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#2f2f4f">Originally posted by Cosmos7777 on 04-12-2001 11:48 AM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">I like Alendora's response.  Raids can be very exciting because of the challenge they represent.  There's the feeling of banding together to accomplish a major objective, of being a part of a team, of achieving mastery in a new area of the game.  However, I would not feel these things if I didn't like the people I was adventuring with, and appreciate their quirks.  

A guild that behaves like a place of work, an office or corporation, is too cold, too impersonal. Gangs of co-workers combining their efforts on a project...I would feel like I was along to operate the photocopier. Quelle drag. No wonder the original poster burned out, there was nothing to keep him focused on the positive.  

I'm only a 55 cleric in a moderate-sized guild, so we don't do Veeshan's Peak, but the tedium of the cleric's duties on the raids we do go on is minimized by the lively chatter, and that we all know each other's personalities from two years of play.

But the cleric's job during raids is tiring.  There's a lot to keep track of, and the need to be constantly alert is draining. I wouldn't want to do more than one or two raids a week, if I could find the time, in any case.</TEXTAREA>
